<strong>Unit: </strong>Population Dynamics

<em>Lesson 3</em>

<em>Textbook</em> (AP Campbell Biology, Tenth Edition; Chapter 54, p. 1208)

<hr />

<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Community Ecology</span></h2>
<span style="font-weight:400;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Community</span>:</span><span style="font-weight:400;"> all the organisms that live together in a place and interact</span>

<span style="font-weight:400;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Community ecology</span>:</span><span style="font-weight:400;"> the study of interactions among all populations in a common environment</span>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Niche</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">An organism’s </span><b>niche</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> is its </span><b>ecological role</b></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight:400;">Habitat = where the organism lives</span>

<span style="font-weight:400;">Niche = the organism’s role, its prey, its predators</span>

<b>Fundamental niche:</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> potential area a species can habitate</span>

<b>Realized niche:</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> the niche that the species can truly occupy due to species interactions</span>

<b>Competitive exclusion: </b><span style="font-weight:400;"> Species 1 has all levels of the ocean floor as a fundamental niche. However, Species 2’s fundamental niche is the bottom half of the ocean floor. To avoid direct competition/competitive exclusion, Species 1’s realized niche is the top half of the ocean floor, and Species 2’s realized niche is the bottom half. That way, they avoid competition.</span>

<span style="font-weight:400;">If there are two types of birds - one with a large beak, and the other with a small beak - but there is only one type of seed to be eaten - a small kind - then the species with the large beak would probably disappear because the other species would outcompete it for food.</span>

<b>No two similar species can occupy the same niche at the same time.</b>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Resource Partitioning</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Reduce competition through </span><b>microhabitats</b></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Differentiation of niches/niche partitioning</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Allows similar species to coexist in a community </span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Each species has a different microhabitat, so they don’t have to directly compete</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">This is evidence of earlier competition, which was resolved by creating different perches</span></li>
</ul>
<em>ex.</em> 7 different types of lizards living in the same forest
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Interspecific Interactions</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Interspecific = between different species</span></li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Symbiotic Interactions</span></h3>
<h4><span style="font-weight:400;">Competition (-/-)</span></h4>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Compete for limited resources</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Competitive exclusion</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Detrimental to both</span></li>
</ul>
<h4><span style="font-weight:400;">Predation/parasitism (-/+)</span></h4>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Predator benefits, prey does not</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Parasite benefits, host does not</span></li>
</ul>
<h4><span style="font-weight:400;">Mutualism (+/+)</span></h4>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Lichens (algae & fungus)</span></li>
</ul>
<h4><span style="font-weight:400;">Commensalism (+/0)</span></h4>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">One species benefits while the other is unaffected</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Barnacles attached to whale</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Predation and competition are the more significant in driving community interactions.</b>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Aloe on a tree = commensalism</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Clownfish and anemone = mutualism</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Spider preying on a butterfly = predation</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Birds that lay their eggs in another bird’s nest = competition</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Obligate mutualism:</b> <span style="font-weight:400;">At least one species cannot survive without the presence of the other species.</span>

<b>Facultative mutualism:</b> <span style="font-weight:400;">Benefits both species but it is not required by either species.</span>

<span style="font-weight:400;">Facultative mutualism is more common because, in obligate mutualism, both species go extinct if one does.</span>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Predation Drives Evolution</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="list-style-type:none;">
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><b>Predators</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> develop </span><b>adaptations </b><span style="font-weight:400;">which allow them to </span><b>locate and subdue prey</b></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
	<li><b>Prey<span style="font-weight:400;"> develop </span>adaptations<span style="font-weight:400;"> which allow them to </span>elude and defend themselves</b></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight:400;">Predation provides a strong selective pressure on both the prey and predator. (ex. Horns, speed, and coloration in animals; spines, thorns, and toxins in plants).</span>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Anti-Predator Adaptations</span></h3>
<span style="font-weight:400;">Anti-predator adaptations allow prey to:</span>

<b>Hide</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> from predators</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Avoid detection</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Camouflage</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Cryptic colouration</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<b>Warn<span style="font-weight:400;"> predators</span></b>
<ul>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Advertise how undesirable the prey is</span></li>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Aposematic </span><span style="font-weight:400;">colouration</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Apo = away & sematic = sign/meaning</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="list-style-type:none;"></li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Mimicry</span></h2>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Batesian Mimicry</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Palatable or harmless species mimic a harmful model</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Result of convergent evolution</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Similar strategies, but are not closely related</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight:400;"><em>ex. </em>The hawkmoth larvae mimic the appearance of the green parrot snake to protect it from being eaten</span>

<span style="font-weight:400;">      The viceroy butterfly mimics the poisonous monarch butterfly</span>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Mullerian Mimicry</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Two or more protected species that look like each other</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Create group defense</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Predators may evolve an innate avoidance</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight:400;"> <em>ex. </em>Wasps, bees, and hornets all have the same colouring to protect them from being eaten.</span>

<b>Common warning colouration:</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> stripes, red, yellow, orange colouration, patches</span>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Coevolution in Community</span></h2>
<span style="font-weight:400;">Species that co-evolve in a mutualistic, predatory, or parasitic relationship become deeply interconnected. These relationships are very intricate and connected so that when one species is affected/changes, the other species are affected too. Relationships that are involved in coevolution are:</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Predator-prey relationships</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Parasite-host relationships</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Flowers & pollinators</span></li>
</ul>
